<?xml version='1.0' encoding='utf-8'?>  
<chapter xml:id="CHAPTERFTC" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Integration in Its Simplest Forms  </title>

  <introduction>
    <title>A Quick Review of Differential Calculus</title>
    <p>
      In <pubtitle>Differential Calculus: From Practice to
      Theory</pubtitle> we saw that the notation for an infinitesimal
      difference, <q><m>\dx{x} </m>,</q> can be thought of as a
      refinement of the <q>change of <m>x</m></q> symbol <m>\Delta
      x</m> which you learned when you were studying straight
      lines. The distinction is that we think of <m>\Delta x =
      x_2-x_1</m> as a measurable distance between <m>x_2</m> and
      <m>x_1</m> whereas <m>\dx{x}</m> represents and infinitesimal
      distance. To be sure we also learned in <pubtitle>Differential
      Calculus: From Practice to Theory</pubtitle> that the notion of
      an infinitesimal is very problematic as a logical foundation of
      our investigations. But as a way of thinking; as an appeal to
      intuition, it can be very useful. Naturally, any conclusions we
      draw from our intuitive approach will have to be confirmed
      logically but we needn<rsq/>t fuss about that yet.
    </p>

    <p>
      By thinking in this way we found that we could extend the idea
      of the slope of a straight line to curved lines. The slope of a
      straight line is given by <m>\frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}</m> (the
      change of <m>y</m> over the change of <m>x</m>) so the slope of
      a curved line at the point <m>x=a</m> is given by the notation
      n<me>\eval{\dfdx{y}{x}}{x}{a} </me>.  It is necessary to specify
      the slope of the curve at the particular point <m>x=a</m>
      because, unlike a straight line, the slope of a curved line
      changes from point to point. 
      This generaled notion slope is very useful. 
    </p>

    <p>
      Our
      interpretation of the differential ratio, <m>\dfdx{y}{x}</m>,
      will vary depending on what physical quantities <m>x</m> and
      <m>y</m> happen to represent. In one simple interpretation if
      the variable <m>y</m> measures a vertical displacement and the
      variable <m>x</m> measures the passage of time then
      <m>\dfdx{y}{t}</m> represents the velocity in the vertical
      direction.
    </p>
    <aside>
      <title>Mathematical Customs</title>
      <p>
        We would probably actually use <m>t</m> instead of <m>x</m> in
        this case in order evoke the word <q>time</q>. The names we
        choose for our variables are generally irrelevant. When it
        matters we choose variable names to help us remember what the
        variable represents. Otherwise we use <q><m>x</m>.</q>
      </p>
    </aside>

    <p>
      For example, the position of a ball tossed
      vertically with an initial velocity <m>v_0</m>, from an initial
      height <m>y_0</m>, will be <me>y(t)=-4.9t^2+v_0t+y_0</me> if
      <m>y</m> is measured in meters and <m>t</m> is measured in
      seconds.
    </p>

    <p>
      Thus the ball<rsq/>s velocity will be <me>v(t) = \dfdx{y}{t} =
      -9.8t+v_0</me> and its acceleration will be
      <me>a(t)=\dfdx{v}{t}=\dfdxn{y}{t}{2}=-9.8,</me> which is, of
      course, the rate of acceleration of an object falling near the
      surface of the earth, as determined experimentally by <url
      href="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Galileo/"
      visual="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Galileo/">Galileo</url>
    </p>

    <p>
      One exercise in <pubtitle>Differential Calculus</pubtitle> asked
      you to show that if <m>y(x)</m> represents the shape of a
      catenary curve then <m>y(x)</m> will satisfy the differential
      equation
      <men xml:id="EQUATIONCatenaryIVP">
        \dfdxn{y}{x}{2} =\frac{w}{H}\sqrt{1+\left(\dfdx{y}{x}\right)^2}.
      </men>
    </p>
    <problem xml:id="DRILLCatenaryRedux">
      <statement>
        <p>
          <idx><h>Catenary</h></idx> 
          A later exercise had you show that in fact the function
          <me>
            y(x)=\frac{H}{w}\left(\frac{e^{\frac{wx}{H}}+e^{\frac{-wx}{H}}}{2}\right)
          </me>
          satisfies <xref ref="CatenaryIVP">equation</xref>. Repeat
          that computation by computing <m>\dfdx{y}{x} </m> and
          <m>\dfdxn{y}{x}{2} </m> and showing that <m>y(x)</m>
          satisfies <xref ref="CatenaryIVP">equation</xref>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </problem>


    <p>
      A natural question is <q>How did we find <m>y(x)</m>?</q>
      Answering that question is the  topic of Integral Calculus. .
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section  xml:id="SECTIONIntegrationAsASum">
    <title>Integration as  Summation</title>
    <p>
      Differential Calculus, in its simplest formulation  is about
      differences  <mdash/> subtraction. That is, given a function
      <m>y=y(x)</m>, when we differentiate it we find the
      infinitesimal difference <mdash/> which we've denoted as
      <m>\dx{y}</m> <mdash/> between two <q>infinitely close</q>
      points. Thus it seems reasonable to suppose that the reverse
      process is about addition <mdash/> summmation. 
    </p>
    <p>
      And indeed it is. <term>Integral Calculus</term>, in its simplest
      formulation is the process of adding up all of the differentials of
      <m>y</m> in order to recover <m>y</m> itself.
    </p>


    <!-- <p>  -->
    <!--   Notice we did not write <me>\int\dx{y} =y</me>.  This is -->
    <!--   because it is not (quite) true. There are an infinite number -->
    <!--   of possible values of <me>\int\dx{y}</me>. Fortunately, as we -->
    <!--   mentioned before, these all differ by constants.  Thus we can -->
    <!--   write something like <m>\int 2x\dx{x}=x^2+C</m> where <m>C</m> -->
    <!--   is an arbitrary constant.  This represents all of the possible -->
    <!--   functions whose derivative is <m>2x</m>, so with that in mind -->
    <!--   <m>\int 2x\dx{x}</m> is referred to as the indefinite integral -->
    <!--   or anti-derivative of <m>2x</m>.  These names come from the -->
    <!--   foundational switch from differentials to limits and -->
    <!--   derivatives, but we still want to emphasize that we integrate -->
    <!--   differentials, not functions (so the <m>\dx{x}</m> is not -->
    <!--   optional). -->
    <!-- </p> -->

    <p> 
      Suppose a point <m>P</m> on the real line begins at <m>P_0</m>
      and traces out a line segment of some unknown length,
      <m>x</m>.

    </p>
    <image source="X0toX.png" width="35%">
      <shortdescription></shortdescription>
    </image>
    <p>
      Notice that in this setting <m>x</m> represents the
      <em>length</em> of the line segment which <m>P</m> has traced
      out. In particular <m>x</m> is <em>not</em> the position
      (coordinate) of <m>P</m> on the line. It can't be because we have
      not specified an origin (zero) point.
    </p>
    <!-- <aside> -->
    <!-- <title>Mathematical Notation</title> -->
    <!-- <p> -->
    <!--  You should always question the meanings of the symbols you encounter -->
    <!--  and use. If you can't state the meaning precisely then you're going -->
    <!--  to have trouble understanding what is being said. For example, we've -->
    <!--  used <m>x</m> to represent the <em>length</em> of a line segment -->
    <!-- </p> -->
    <!-- <p> -->
    <!--   Sometimes it will be convenient to call the line <q>the <m>x</m>-axis.</q> But this -->
    <!--   is a bit confusing as we<rsq/>ve already used <m>x</m> to indicate a -->
    <!--   position on the line.  Using <m>x</m> in two incompatible ways like -->
    <!--   this is not precise enough for mathematics and we shouldn't really -->
    <!--   do it. Nor should you. But, for better or worse mathematics is done, -->
    <!--   and learned, by flawed and imprecise human creatures so we have to -->
    <!--   find ways to cope with our foibles. -->

    <!-- </p> -->
    <!-- </aside> -->
    <p>
      In sketch below we have partitioned the line segment between <m>P</m> and <m>P_0</m> (which
      we have re-labeled <m>x_n</m> and <m>x_0</m> in the sketch below)
      into subintervals.
    </p>
    <image source="FTC1.png" width="50%">
      <shortdescription></shortdescription>
    </image>
    <p>
      We represent the length of the  first subinterval of <m>x</m> with <m>\Delta
      x_1</m>, of the second with <m>\Delta x_2</m>, and so on.  In
      general if <m>\Delta{x_i}</m> represents the length of <m>i</m>th
      subinterval of <m>x</m>. Clearly the length of the line
      segment is
      <md>
        <mrow>\Delta{x_1}+\Delta{x_2}+\Delta{x_3} +\cdots  +\Delta{x_{n-1}}+\Delta{x_n}</mrow>
        <mrow> =  (x_1-x_0)+(x_2-x_1)+(x_3-x_2) +\cdots + (x_{n-1}-x_{n-2})+(x_n-x_{n-1})</mrow>
        <mrow>=x_n-x_0.</mrow>
      </md>
      If the subintervals are all the same length, say
      <m>\Delta{x}</m>, then we no longer need the subscripts to
      distinguish them so we could write
      <me> \underbrace{\Delta{x}+\Delta{x} + \cdots{}+\Delta{x}}_{\text{n
      copies}}=x_n-x_0</me>
      
      instead.  But this is cumbersome and we are far to lazy to write
      all of that each time we want to indicate such a sum.  Leibniz proposed using 
      the letter <q>S</q> (first letter of the word <q>sum</q>) to
      simplify the summation  notation:


      <men xml:id="EQUATIONFinDiffSum">
        \int{}\Delta{x}=\underbrace{\Delta{x}+\Delta{x} + \cdots{}+\Delta{x}}_{\text{n
      copies}} = x_n-x_0 </men>
      and his idea has been universally adopted.
    </p> 
    <p> 
      We assume, with Leibniz, that <xref
      ref="FinDiffSum">equation</xref> remains true when the finite
      differences (<m>\Delta{x}</m>) are replaced with infinitesimal
      differences (<m>\dx{x}{}</m>): <men
      xml:id="EQUATIONDefInt2">\int{\dx{x}{}}=x_n-x_0.</men>
      The symbol 
      <q><m>\int </m></q> is called an 
      <term>integral sign</term>, and any expression starting with 
      <q><m>\int </m> </q> and ending with 
      <q><m>\dx{x} </m></q> is called an 
      <term>integral</term>. <xref ref="EQUATIONDefInt2">Equation</xref> is the simplest possible integral.
    </p>
    <aside>
      <title>A Little History</title>
      <p>
        Leibniz chose the letter <q>S</q> because
        it is the first letter of Latin word <foreign>summa</foreign>,
        from which we get the English word <q>sum.</q>
      </p>
      <p>
        To a modern eye the integral sign looks like a stylized
        letter <q>S,</q> and that is often how it is described. But
        it isn<rsq/>t stylized at all. When Calculus was invented in
        the seventeenth century a printed letter <q>S</q> typically
        had several forms, depending on where it appeared in a
        word. In one of these forms it extended above and below the
        line of text, much like the modern form of the letter
        <q>f</q> extends above the line of text.  Leibniz adopted
        this doubly extended form of <q>S</q> as his summation, or
        integral, sign. So the integral symbol isn<rsq/>t stylized,
        but it is archaic.
      </p>
    </aside>

    <p>
      <xref ref="EQUATIONDefInt2">Equation</xref> says that if we add
      up the lengths of all of the differentials that make up the
      line segment from <m>x_0</m> to <m>x_n</m> we will get its
      length, <m>x_n-x_0</m>, which we have called <m>x</m>. Therefore
      <men   xml:id="EQUATIONFTCSimple">\int\dx{x}=x.</men>
    </p>
    <p>
      This is surely not surprising to you and you are probably
      wondering why we've taken the trouble to wrap such an obvious
      statement in this arcane notation. The reason is this: <xref
      ref="EQUATIONFTCSimple">Equation</xref> is a very simple form
      of what is known as the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus and we
      will need to become very comfortable with it. Later, when
      things get complex, it will be helpful to refer back to <xref
      ref="EQUATIONFTCSimple">equation</xref> and remind ourselves
      that, at its heart, integration is about adding up differentials.
    </p>

    <paragraphs  xml:id="PARAGRAPHCoordinatesAndVariables">
      <title>DIGRESSION: Coordinates and  Variable Names</title>
      <p>
        You may also be wondering why we are being so punctilious about
        distinguishing the label of a point <m>P</m>, and its coordinate
        <m>x_n</m>. A natural response would be <q>Aren<rsq/>t they the same
        thing?</q>
      </p>
      <p> No, actually they aren<rsq/>t. The label of a point is the
      name we use to distinguish it from other points. The
      (horizontal) coordinate of a point is it<rsq/>s (horizontal)
      distance from the origin.  Consider the following diagram.<!--
      Suppose <m>P</m> is a point on -->
      <!-- the <m>x</m>-axis located at a distance of <m>x</m> to the right of -->
      <!-- the origin. Does <m>x</m> represent a length? If so, what is <m>x</m> -->
      <!-- the length of? -->
      </p>
      <image source="VarX2.png" width="60%">
        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
      </image>
      <p>
        The labels (names) of the two points are <m>P_0</m> and <m>P</m>. Since
        <m>x_0</m> measures the distance between zero and <m>P_0</m> it is by
        definition the coordinate of <m>P_0</m>. (If a vertical axis were
        present <m>x_0</m> would be the first coordinate and zero would be the
        second.) Similarly <m>x_n</m> is the coordinate of <m>P</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        On the
        other hand since <m>x</m> <mdash/> the distance between <m>P_0</m> and
        <m>P</m> <mdash/> is not measured from the origin it is
        neither a coordinate nor the label of a point. 
      <!-- <p> -->
      <!-- Do you see -->
      <!-- what<rsq/>s going on here? The cooordinate <m>x</m> is indeed the length of the line segment between the origin and <m>P</m>. By definition every coordinate is the length of a line segment. But not every length  is necessarily a cooordinate. To see why consider the following sketch.  -->
      <!-- </p> -->
      <!-- <image source="VarX2.png" width="60%"> -->
      <!-- <shortdescription></shortdescription> -->
      <!-- </image> -->
      <!-- <p> -->
      <!-- In this case <m>P</m> and <m>P_0</m> are the labels of the two points, -->
      <!-- whereas <m>x_n</m> and <m>x_0</m> are their coordinates, respectively. -->
      <!-- </p> -->
        It is the length of the line segment
        <m>\overline{P_0P}</m>. If we partition this line segment and
        compute <m>\int\dx{x} </m> we get 
        <me>\int\dx{x}=x=x_n-x_0</me> 
        which is equivalent to <xref
        ref="EQUATIONFTCSimple">equation</xref>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Since coordinates distinguish one point from another as well as
        their labels do,   a (very) common practice is to dispense with the
        labels altogether and make the coordinates serve both purposes as in
        the diagram below.
      </p>
      <image source="VarX3.png" width="60%">
        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
      </image>
      <p>
        Strictly speaking this is an abuse of our notation and it can cause
        confusion because it isn<rsq/>t always clear whether <m>x_0</m> and
        <m>x_n</m> refer to points on the line, or their distance from the
        origin (their coordinates). Always be sure it is clear to you which
        usage is intended.
      </p>

<p><alert>END OF DIGRESSION</alert></p>
    </paragraphs>


  </section>

  <section  xml:id="SECTIONIntAsAntiDiff">
    <title>Integration as Antidifferentiation</title>

    <definition  xml:id="DEFINITIONAntiderivative">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose we have a function <men
          xml:id="EQUATIONDefAntideriv">y=F(t)</men> whose derivative is
          <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=f(t)</m>. Then <m>F(t)</m> is called an 
          <term>antiderivative</term> of <m>f(t)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      It follows immediately that if a function has one antiderivative
      then it has infinitely many since, by the Constant Rule, adding
      a constant to a function will not change its derivative. Thus if
      we know that <m>F(x)</m> is one antiderivative of <m>f(x)</m>,
      then we know all (infinitely many) of the antiderivatives of
      <m>f(x)</m> because we get a (slightly) different antiderivative
      each time we add a constant to <m>F(x)</m>.  Remember this. We
      will return to it when we discuss <xref
      ref="EQUATIONFTC">equation</xref> below.
    </p>
    <p>
      Returning to <xref ref="EQUATIONDefAntideriv">equation</xref>, we
      know from our study of Differential Calculus that
      
      <me>\dx{y}=F^\prime(t)\dx{t}=f(t)\dx{t},</me>

      and we know from our work in 
      <xref ref="SECTIONIntegrationAsASum"></xref> that
      
      <men xml:id="EQUATIONFTC2">y=\int\dx{y}</men>. 

      Therefore 

      <me>y=\int\dx{y}= \int f(t)\dx{t}.</me>

      Observe that since <m>\dx{y} </m> is a differential it follows
      that <m>f(t)\dx{t}</m> is also a differential so the expression
      <m>\int f(t)\dx{t}</m> is a valid integral.
    </p>

    <p>
      Thus it appears that if <m>\dx{y}=f(t)\dx{t} </m> is known then
      <m>y=F(t)</m>, will be the antiderivative of <m>f(t)</m>. That is to
      say, integration appears to be <q>differentiation run backwards.</q>
    </p>

    <paragraphs xml:id="PARAGRAPHSDiffNotFunc"> <title>We Integrate
    Differentials, Not Functions</title> 
    <p>
       Integration can be usefully thought of as either summation or
       antidifferentiation. But the integral sign is designed to
       indicate the summation of differentials, not
       antidifferentiation.  It is thus very easy to use the notation
       improperly. Sooner or later most people will fall into the
       habit of dropping the final <q><m>\dx{t}{}</m></q>, writing
      <md>
        <mrow>\amp{}\int f(t) \amp{}\text{ instead of }\amp{}\amp{}\int f(t)\dx{t},</mrow>
      </md>
      and calling them both the integral of the function
      <m>f(t)</m>. This is an unfortunate, but common, abuse of the
      notation.  We <em>strongly</em> suggest that you take care to
      avoid this bad habit for as long as you can. Especially when the
      concepts are still new it can be very confusing.
    </p>

    <!-- <aside> -->
    <!--   <title>Mathematical Customs</title> -->

    <!--   <p> -->
    <!--     In practice, if they are not relevant to the discussion at hand the -->
    <!--     indices are frequently left out entirely. -->
    <!--   </p> -->

    <!-- </aside> -->

<aside>
<title>Mathematical Notation</title>
<p>
By calling <m>\int f(t)</m> meaningless we have overstated the
situation a bit. If you study mathematics long enough you will
encounter situations where this is a perfectly reasonable notation to
use. But we will not encounter them here, and it is best if you
don<rsq/>t fall into this habit while you are still learning the
basics.
</p>
</aside>

    <p>
      Remember that <me>\int f(t)</me> is meaningless no matter how
      convenient it might be because it indicates that we are summing
      a function, not a differential.. But the meaning of <me>\int
      f(t)\dx{t}</me> is clear: We're summing up all of the
      differentials of the form <m>f(t)\dx{t} </m>.
    </p>

    <!-- <p> -->
    <!--   Suppose that <m>y=t^2</m> then <m>\dx{y} =2t\dx{t}</m>. Then -->
    <!--   <m>\int 2t\dx{t}</m> makes sense because the product -->
    <!--   <m>2t\dx{t}=\dx{y}</m> is a differential. But <m>\int 2t</m> -->
    <!--   is nonsense because <m>2t</m> alone is not a differential. -->
    <!-- </p> -->
    <!-- <p> -->
    <!--   In particular, <m>\int 2t</m> is meaningless. However  if <m>y=t^2</m> -->
    <!--   then what is probably meant is -->
    <!--   <men  xml:id="EQUATIONPlusCMissing">\int 2t\dx{t} = \int \dx{y}</men> which is equal to <m>y</m> since <m>\int \dx{y}</m> means  -->
    <!--   <q>add up the differentials of <m>y</m>.</q> -->
    <!-- </p> -->
</paragraphs>

    <p>
      This is true as far as it goes, but remember that the title of this
      chapter is <q>Integration in its <em>Simplest</em> Form.</q> Running
      differentiation backwards is not as straightforward as it first
      appears to be.
    </p>


    <example xml:id="EXAMPLESimpleInt1">
      <title>A Simple Integration</title>
      <p>
        For example, can you find a formula for this integral?
        <me>\int2t\dx{t}</me>
      </p>
      <p>
        In this example clearly, <m>f(t)=2t</m>. Thus from <xref
        ref="DEFINITIONAntiderivative"></xref> we see that <m>F(t) =
        \frac{t^2}{2}</m> is an antiderivative, and we can capture all of the
        antiderivatives by adding an arbitrary constant, traditionally called
        <q><m>C</m>,</q> and we write 
        <me>\int 2t\dx{t} = \frac{t^2}{2} + C.</me>
      </p>
      <p>
        As this example shows the expression <m>\int f(t)\dx{t} </m>
        represents a multifunction like the <q> <m>\text{arc}</m></q>
        functions we encountered when we learned to differentiate the
        trigonometric functions and their inverses.
      </p>
      <p>
        There will be times when we will want to choose only one of
        the functions represented by <m>\int f(t)\dx{t}</m>. This will
        consist entirely of choosing the value of <m>C</m> that works
        for our problem. None of the complex domain and range
        difficulties that caused do many headaches with the inverse
        trigonometric functions will be in play here. Since the
        multifunction that will come up for us are so simple, we will
        dispence with the formal language and call <m>F(t) =
        \frac{t^2}{2}+C</m> the <term>most general
        antiderivative</term> of <m>f(t) = t^2</m>, but it is really a
        multfunction since <q><m>C</m></q> is unspecified.
      </p>
    </example>


    <p>
        Modern integration theory has expanded considerably beyond
        what we will be learning in this course. But the underlying
        notions of the integral as a sum and the integral as an
        antiderivative are still very helpful and we will rely on them
        rather heavily, at least at first.
      </p>

<problem  xml:id="PROBLEMAntiDiffPractice">
<p>
Find the most general antiderivative.
<ol cols="2" marker="i">
<li>
<m>\int t^2\dx{t}</m>
</li>
<li>
<m>\int 3t-2\dx{t}</m>
</li>
<li>
<m>\int 7\dx{t}</m>
</li>
<li>
<m>\int \sin(t)\dx{t}</m>
</li>
<li>
<m>\int \cos(t)\dx{t}</m>
</li>
<li>
<m>\int \sec(t)\tan(t)\dx{t}</m>
</li>
<li>
<m>\int e^t\dx{t}</m>
</li>
<li>
<m>\int t^{-1}\dx{t}</m>
</li>
</ol>
</p>
</problem>

<exercise xml:id="EXERCISEAntiDerivPractice">
<introduction>
<p>
<idx><h>Antiderivative</h></idx>
Show that  the following statements are true.
</p>
</introduction>
<task>
<statement>
<p>
    <m>\int 2te^{t^2}\dx{t} = e^{t^2} +C</m>
</p>
</statement>
</task>
<task>
<statement>
<p>
<m>\int te^t\dx{t} = (t-1)e^t+C</m>
</p>
</statement>
</task>
<task>
<statement>
<p>
<m>\int \sin(x)\cos(x)\dx{x} =\frac12\sin^2(x)+C</m>
</p>
</statement>
</task>
<task  xml:id="PROBLEMSinsqcossqantider">
<statement>
<p>
<m>\int \sin(x)\cos(x)\dx{x} = -\frac12\cos^2(x)+C</m>
</p>
<p>
Notice that we<rsq/>ve used <m>x</m> instead of <m>t</m> for our
variable. Does that matter? Explain.
</p>
</statement>
</task>
<task>
<statement>
<p>
<m>\int u\cos(u) \dx{u} = u\sin(u)+\cos(u)+C</m>
</p>
</statement>
</task>
<task>
<statement>
<p>
<m>\int x\ln(x) \dx{x} = x(\ln{x}-1)+C</m>
</p>
</statement>
</task>


</exercise>

  </section>
<section>
    <title>Rules for Integration</title>
    <p>
      Since Integration can be thought of as the reverse of
      Differentiation (at least in the first approximation) it is not
      too surprising to learn that each differentiation rule has its
      integration rule counterpart.  The following table illustrates
      some of these rules.
    </p>
    
    <table xml:id="TABLEBasicIntegrationTable">
      <title>Integration Rules Inherited from Differentiation Rules</title>
      <tabular halign="center">
        <row bottom="major" header="yes">
          
          <cell></cell><cell>Differentiation Rule</cell><cell><line>Integration
          Rule</line><line> (Assume <m>a</m> and <m>c</m> are
          constants.)  </line></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
<cell>1</cell>          <cell><m>\dx(\text{constant})=0</m></cell>
          <cell><line><m>\int0\dx{x}=c,</m></line> <line> where <m> c
          </m> is a constant.</line></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
<cell>2</cell>          <cell><m>\dx(f+g)=\dx{f}+\dx{g}</m></cell>
          <cell><line><m>\int\dx(f+g)=\int\dx{f}+\int\dx{g}</m></line>
<line><m>=f+g+c</m></line></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
<cell>3</cell>          <cell><line>If <m>a</m> is a constant, then</line>
          <line><m>\dx(ay)=a\dx(y)</m></line>
          </cell>
          <cell>
          <line><m>\int a\dx{y}=\int\dx(ay)=a\int\dx{y}</m></line>
<line><m>=ay+c</m></line></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
<cell>4</cell>          <cell><m>\dx(x^{n+1})=(n+1)x^n\dx{x}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\int x^n\dx{x} = \frac{x^{n+1}}{n+1}+c, n\neq
          -1</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
<cell>5</cell>          <cell><m>\dx(\ln(x))=\frac1x\dx{x}=x^{-1}\dx{x}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\int x^{-1}\dx{x} = \ln\abs{x}+c</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
<cell>6</cell>          <cell><m>\dx(e^x)= e^x\dx{x}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\int e^x\dx{x} = e^x+c</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
<cell>7</cell>          <cell><m>\dx(\sin(x))=\cos(x)\dx{x}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\int \cos(x) = \sin(x) +c</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
<cell>8</cell>          <cell><m>\dx(\cos(x))=-\sin(x)\dx{x}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\int \sin(x)\dx{x} = -\cos(x) +c</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
<cell>9</cell>          <cell><m>\dx(\tan(x))=\sec^2(x)\dx{x}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\int\sec^2(x)\dx{x} = \tan(x)+c</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
<cell>10</cell>          <cell><m>\dx(\sec(x))= \sec(x)\tan(x)\dx{x}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\int\sec(x)\tan(x)=\sec(x)+c</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
<cell>11</cell>          <cell><m>\dx(\inverse\sin(x))=
          \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}\dx{x}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\int\frac{1}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}\dx{x}=\inverse\sin(x)+c</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
<cell>12</cell>          <cell><m>\dx(\inverse\tan(x))=
          \frac{1}{1+x^2}\dx{x}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\int\frac{1}{1+x^2}\dx{x}=\inverse\tan(x)+c</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
<cell>13</cell>          <cell><m>\dx(\inverse\sec(x))=
          \frac{1}{x\sqrt{x^2-1}}\dx{x}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\int\frac{1}{x\sqrt{x^2-1}}\dx{x}=\inverse\sec(x)+c</m></cell>
        </row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
    
    
    <p>
      <xref ref="BasicIntegrationTable">Table</xref> is not
      exhaustive. It couldn<rsq/>t possibly be since every
      differentiation formula gives rise to a corresponding
      integration formula. 
</p>
<p> 
  Conspicuously absent from <xref
  ref="BasicIntegrationTable">Table</xref> are the Product Rule, the
  Quotient Rule, and the Chain Rule.  The reverse of the Quotient Rule
  is rather limited in its applicability and typically is not used.
   Reversing the others can be quite useful and will be covered
  later.
</p>
<p>
  If you read each of these Differentiation and Integration Rules
  verbally you can hear that they reverse each other. For example in
  line 4 we see that to differentiate <m>x</m> to a power, we
  <q>multiply by the exponent and then subtract one from the
  exponent.</q> To reverse the process, we <q>add one to the exponent
  and then divide by the exponent.</q> (In the same way that when
  dressing you put your socks on and then your shoes and to reverse it
  you take off your shoes first and then your socks). </p>
<p>
  Notice that the Integration Rule in line 4 will not work if the
  exponent is <m>n=-1</m> as you cannot divide by zero. But that
  apparent hole in the table is covered on line 5. Does it seem odd to
  you that the we need the natural logarithm to plug that hole? After
  all, line 4 is about powers of the variable, which is a fairly
  concrete idea, whereas the natural logarithm function is much more
  abstract
</p>
<p>
While we are at line five, notice that we have
  inserted an absolute value in the formula:
      <me>
        \int\inverse x\dx{x}=\ln\abs{x}+C.
      </me>
    </p>
    
    
    <problem>
      <statement>
        <p>
          One way to define the absolute value function is
          <m>\abs{x}=\sqrt{x^2}</m> where his signifies the
          non-negative square root.  For example,
          <m>\abs{3}=\sqrt(3^2)=\sqrt(9)=3</m> and
          <m>\abs{-3}=\sqrt{(-3)^2}=\sqrt{9}=3</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Show that with this definition of absolute value, we still
          obtain the formula
          <me>
            \dx(\ln\abs{x})=\frac1x \dx{x}.
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>
          Be careful that you do not try to take the logarithm of a
          negative number. A common practice is to write
          <m>\int\inverse x\dx{x}=\ln(x)+C</m>, even though this is
          only valid for <m>x\gt{0}</m>.  We will adopt this practice, and resort to
          an absolute value only when there is an issue about being
          negative.
        </p>
      </hint>
    </problem>
    
    
    <problem>
      <p>
        It looks like we broke our own rule in lines two and three in
        the above table of integration rules.  After all,
        <me>
          \int \dx{f} +\int \dx{g} = f+c_1+g+c_2
        </me>
        where and are arbitrary constants, and
        <me>
          a\int\dx{y}=a(y+c)=ay+ac </me>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Explain why what we have in the table is still legitimate.
      </p>
    </problem>
    
    <p>
      In light of the above problem, practitioners often will perform
      the integration of a differential applying whatever tools are
      appropriate and then combining any arbitrary constants into one
      constant at the end.  For example, consider
      
      <md>
        <mrow>
          \int\left(5x^2-3\sqrt{x}+\frac{2}{1+x^2}\right)\dx{x}\amp
          =5\int x^2\dx{x}-3\int x^\frac12
          \dx{x}+2\int\frac{1}{1+x^2}\dx{x}
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
          \amp =5\left(\frac{x^3}{3}\right) -
          \frac{3\left(x^{\frac12}\right)}{\frac32} +
          2\inverse\tan(x)+c
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
          \amp =\frac53x^3-2x^{\frac32}+2\inverse\tan(x)+c.
        </mrow>
      </md>
      As with differentiation rules, when you get more comfortable
      with the integration rules, you will probably do these in your
      head.  Again, developing this fluency this is why you need to
      practice.
    </p>
</section>

<section  xml:id="SECTIONIVPS">
<title>Differential Equations and Initial Value Problems</title>

<p>
Calculus gives us an extraordinarily powerful set of tools for
modeling real world phenomena. We have already some simple examples of
this already when we studied differentiation. For example if <m>y(t)</m> is the height
of a falling body we know that the acceleration of the body is given
by the second derivative of position: <m>\dfdxn{y}{t}{2}</m>. Moreover   Galileo 
showed that a body falling freely near the surface of the earth would
accelerate downward at a constant rate we<rsq/>ve called <m>g</m>. This is fully described by
the differential equation
<me>\dfdxn{y}{t}{2}=g,</me> 
which is our model of a falling body. From this model and the
procedures of Different 
Calculus we can recover  functions which tell us the velocity and the
position of a falling body at any time and under any starting conditions.
We will have more to say about this particular model in <xref
ref="SECTIONProjectileMotion"></xref>. 
</p>

    <p>
    Recall also that if <m>y(x)</m> is the shape that a hanging chain
    naturally settles into under the pull of gravity then <m>y(x)</m>
    will necessarily be a solution of the <term>Differential
    Equation</term>:
      <men  xml:id="EQUATIONHangChainModel">
        \dfdxn{y}{x}{2} =
        \frac{w}{H}\sqrt{1+\left(\dfdx{y}{x}\right)^2}.
      </men>
which is a model for the Hanging Chain problem. The graph of a
function which solves <xref ref="EQUATIONHangChainModel">equation</xref> will
be  the shape of a hanging chain.
    </p>

<problem  xml:id="DRILLHangingChainSolution">
<p>
Show that               <men  xml:id="EQUATIONCatenary1">
                y=\frac{H}{w}
                \left(\frac{e^{\frac{wx}{H}}+e^{-\frac{wx}{H}}}{2}\right)
              </men>
 solves <xref ref="EQUATIONHangChainModel">equation</xref>.
</p>
</problem>



<p>
It is one thing to confirm a given solution, as in <xref
ref="DRILLHangingChainSolution"></xref>, but finding the solution in
the first place is not at all a simple task.  A start might be to let
<m>z=\dfdx{y}{x}</m>, so we have
      
      <md>
        <mrow>
          \dfdx{z}{x}\amp=\frac{w}{H}\sqrt{1+z^2}
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
          \frac{1}{\sqrt{1+z^2}}\dx{z}\amp =\frac{w}{H}\dx{x}.
        </mrow>
      </md>
      If we now integrate both sides we get
      <me>
        \int\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+z^2}}\dx{z}=\int\frac{w}{H}\dx{x}.
      </me>
    </p>
    
    <p>
      The right-hand side of this doesn't pose any problems since
      <m>\frac{w}{H}</m> is a constant.  However, the left-hand side
      is another matter, since it doesn't quite fit with anything in
      our table.  We will learn techniques to handle such situations,
      but first let's look at some applications of integration which
      utilize what we know.
      </p>

  <definition xml:id="DEFINITIONIVP">
    <title>Initial Value Problem (IVP)</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        <!-- \label{def:IVP} -->
        An <term>Initial Value Problem</term> is a differential
        equation of the form <me>\dfdx{y}{x}=f(x,y),</me> along with
        an <term>Initial Value</term> <me>y(x_0)=y_0.</me>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>


</section>


</chapter>
